# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2023-grand-national
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The **1836 Grand Liverpool Steeplechase** was the first of three unofficial annual precursors of a steeplechase which later became known as the Grand National.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The steeplechase was held at Aintree Racecourse near Liverpool, England on 29 February 1836 and attracted a field of ten runners.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The winning horse was The Duke, ridden by Captain Martin Becher in the violet with white sleeves and cap colours of Mr Sirdefield, the landlord of the *George Inn* in Great Crosby and was trained privately.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The race was won in a time of 15 minutes 12 seconds, over twice the present course record.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The race was a selling race and its status as an official Grand National was revoked some time between 1862 and 1873.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] For many years the course set for this race was thought to be at Maghull, with even the honours board at Aintree stating such.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] However, contemporary reports state with no doubt that the course was Aintree, and the same, which was used for every other race bar those, which took place at Gatwick during the First World War.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The Start was at the same point where most Nationals would commence from the 1860s until the early 21st century, just in front of the stands, facing out towards the line of country the runners would take.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] There was no set number of created fences and instead the runners had to navigate a course as best they could.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] What potential obstacles they encountered along the way could be either jumped or navigated around, just as long as they remained outside a set of flags, which marked the inner line of the course.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Therefore running around a fence, would not disqualify a horse as it would today.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The course had many lanes around it that a rider could take if they felt it more advantageous than jumping the banks from field to field.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The potential obstacles they would encounter if they followed the expected line of country to be run.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] **Fence 1** A formidable bank out of a lane topped with furze, **Fence 2** Stiff fence, **Fence 3** Stiff fence, **Fence 4** Stiff fence, **Fence 5** Brook.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] However, there were several lanes and gates a competitor could navigate around the Canal side of the course, avoiding many of these fences.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] If they jumped them all then the last fence before entering the race course proper again would be **Fence 12** An awkward rail onto a paved road.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The runners then had a half mile to cover to reach **Fence 13** Stiff hurdle well matted with furze, **Fence 14** Stiff hurdle well matted with furze.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] They then passed the grandstand and would cover the same ground again.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The race got off to a poor start when all ten runners refused at the first obstacle, *Derry* turning and leading the way at the second attempt.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Once past that, the field continued around the first circuit without incident, although *Gulliver* and *Cowslip* were tailed off and looking distressed when they came back in sight in front of the stands, both being pulled up, rather than take the second circuit.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Prior to the race it was ordered that one particular gate out of a lane near the paved road would remain nailed open so that the runners could pass.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] However, one spectator took exception to this and either by design, or just not realising, freed and closed the gate after the first circuit.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Horatio Powell, on board the favourite, *Laurie Todd* took this route on the first circuit and again on the second, not expecting the gate ahead to now be closed.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The obstacle proved too high for the favourite to jump and the horse became the first to fall in the race.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Powell was quickly on his feet and making a bid to remount when another competitor, Most likely Bretherton aboard *Cock-A-Hoop*, knocked him back to the ground.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] While there appears to have been some whispers that this act was deliberate, the fact Powell made no objection after the race suggest he at least believed the collision to have been mere accident.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Either way, *Laurie Todd* backer's had lost their money.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The chances of *Cock-A-Hoop* and *Percy* were fading by this stage as they were losing ground on the two leaders and by the time they came in sight of the stands, they were battling for third pace.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Both were briefly offered hope as the two leaders, *The Duke* and *Polyanthus* both blundered at the final hurdle before going on to dispute the finish.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] *The Duke* prevailed by one length with *Polyanthus* finishing second.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The race was completed in fifteen minutes and 12 seconds, taking almost half as long again as the course would be covered in an average future Grand National, suggesting it was either cantered at a very slow pace or the runners encountered more issues than the reporters on course recorded.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The race largely failed to capture the public imagination and came in for scathing comments from some of the local press.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] By the time the first Grand National historians began emerging in the early 1860s this race, and the two which would follow in 1837 and 1838, had largely been forgotten by the passing of time and fading memories.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] As a result, when the first honours board was erected at Aintree in the early 1890s this race was totally omitted and remained forgotten for over a century before being rediscovered early in the 21st century.
[src:2023-grand-national/1836-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] It is still regarded officially by Aintree as not being worthy of Grand National status and is instead regarded as the first of three unofficial precursors over the same course.
[src:2023-grand-national/1837-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The **1837 Grand Liverpool Steeplechase** was the second of three unofficial annual precursors of a Handicap Steeple-chase, later to become known as the Grand National Steeplechase horse race which took place at Aintree Racecourse near Liverpool on 4 March 1837 and attracted a field of four runners.
[src:2023-grand-national/1837-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] This race did not carry the prestige of the future Grand Nationals and its status as an official Grand National was revoked some time between 1862 and 1873.
[src:2023-grand-national/1837-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Four horses lined up for the start of the race for which starting prices were recorded by the Liverpool Mail.
[src:2023-grand-national/1837-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The race was won in a time of fourteen minutes, beating the previous year's time by five minutes and fifty seconds.
[src:2023-grand-national/1837-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The race would go on to be regarded as the second running of the Grand National until the mid-1860s when newspapers began omitting the race, and those of 1836 and 1838, from the records of previous winners.
[src:2023-grand-national/1837-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Although it is now widely acknowledged that the race was indeed run at Aintree, it is also the official view of Aintree that the races prior to 1839 should not be included as legitimate Grand Nationals and should be regarded more as precursors.
[src:2023-grand-national/1837-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] As a result, *The Duke* is not listed in official publications as a dual winner of the race.
[src:2023-grand-national/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] This race did not carry the prestige of the future Grand Nationals and its status as an official Grand National was revoked sometime between 1862 and 1873.
[src:2023-grand-national/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Three competitors faced the starter and were quoted as follows.
[src:2023-grand-national/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The race had been delayed due to the weather and the resulting clash with the much more prestigious St Albans chase saw a field of competitors that failed to capture the imagination of the public.
[src:2023-grand-national/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The waning finances of the race organiser, William Lynn resulted in a committee being formed to try to boost the race.
[src:2023-grand-national/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] For many years after this event the race was regarded as the third running of the Grand National by racegoers and pressmen alike, however this stance began to change during the 1860s when national newspapers began listing the former winners of the National back only as far as 1839.
[src:2023-grand-national/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] When the official honours board at Aintree was erected in 1894 it stated that the race of 1838 was run at a nearby course in Maghull and that the winner was a horse named Sir Henry, ridden by Mr Olliver against nine rivals.
[src:2023-grand-national/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] Racing returns from this period show that racing at Maghull ceased in 1835 and that there was no horse in training in 1838 named Sir Henry.
[src:2023-grand-national/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] The only jockey named Olliver in racing at the time was Tom Olliver and on the date of the race he was riding at St Albans.
[src:2023-grand-national/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] For over a century the detail recorded on the honours board was accepted as fact until evidence was presented to show the real events of the 1838 Great Liverpool chase.
[src:2023-grand-national/1838-grand-liverpool-steeplechase] While it is now accepted among the majority of racing writers that the 1838 race was indeed run at Aintree and not Maghull it is still the official view that the lack of prestige in the race prior to 1839 warrants its continued omission from being declared an official Grand National.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] The **1839 Grand Liverpool Steeplechase** was the first official annual running of a steeplechase which later became known as the Grand National.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] It was held at Aintree Racecourse near Liverpool, England, on Tuesday 26 February 1839 and attracted a field of 17 runners.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] Although recorded by the press at the time as the fourth running of the Grand Liverpool Steeplechase, which was renamed the Grand National in 1847, the first three runnings were poorly organised affairs possibly run at Maghull.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] This year the race came under new management and the arrival of the railway in Liverpool made travel to the course easier.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] The race was not run as a handicap chase (the Grand National was converted to a handicap race in 1843) and therefore all the runners carried twelve stone.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] Eighteen runners were declared to run in the race but shortly before the start Jerry was withdrawn.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] The start was situated near to where the modern day Melling Road is and took the runners out into open countryside, jumping a line of natural banks, no more than 2 feet (0.61 m) high before reaching a post and rails over a brook.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] They then took the runners left towards the Leeds and Liverpool Canal, turning sharply (where the modern day Canal Turn is) to run along the canalside back towards the racecourse, negotiating the Second Brook (the modern day Valentine's Brook).
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] The runners would then enter the 'racecourse proper' at the far end of the circuit to run back towards the stands, jumping a plain fence (the modern day Chair) before jumping a wall topped with gorse (the modern day Water Jump).
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] The field then took another circuit of the course, this time bypassing the final two obstacles towards the finishing post.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] Paulina refused the first jump but continued after being put at the fence a second time.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] The most famous incident of the race occurred at the fence then known as the First Brook.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] Captain Becher had taken Conrad into second place at this stage but his mount failed to clear the rails and fell.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] Becher was forced to dive for cover into the brook itself as the other horses cleared the obstacle and legend has it that he was heard to tell the spectators that he did not realise how filthy water tasted without the benefit of whisky.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] Seconds later, William McDonough joined Becher in the brook after falling from Rust but it was the Captain's name attributed to the fence, now known as Becher's Brook.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] Both riders remounted but Becher's race ended when his mount fell again at the Second Brook where both Barkston and Cannon Ball had also fallen.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] It was one of these horses, while running loose, who ended the hopes of the favourite when The Nun was brought down shortly before rejoining the racecourse; she was remounted by Tom Ferguson while Rust was pulled up before reaching the stands.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] Charity fell at the wall in front of the stands but was also remounted.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] Railroad led at this stage with Lottery in second place but so slow was the pace of the race and so wide the distances between competitors that the favourite The Nun had managed to make up ground to move into third.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] On the second circuit, Charity fell before reaching the First Brook for the second time while Dictator fell at the fence situated at the turn by the canal but was quickly remounted by Robert Carlin.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] Jem Mason took Lottery into the lead at the First Brook and maintained it to the finish, winning more easily than the three-length margin suggested in a time of 14 minutes 53 seconds, 53 seconds outside the course record.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] Lottery was prepared for the race at the stables of George Dockeray in Epsom, who is loosely regarded as the trainer but most of the preparation was more likely conducted by the owner, Piccadilly horse dealer John Elmore in whose colours of blue jacket and black cap the jockey rode.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] Seventy-Four was second, Paulina third and True Blue fourth.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] Pioneer was on course to finish third when he unseated his rider.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] Walker quickly remounted but could only manage fifth place.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] Although regarded at the time as the fourth running of the Grand Liverpool Steeplechase, this running went on to be regarded as the first official running of the Grand National.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] The finishing order was only loosely recorded in the press as Jack in sixth, The Nun seventh, Railroad eighth, Rambler ninth and Cramp the last of ten to pass the post.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] Later record books show seven finishers though this is not supported by any press reports from the time.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] There was also much criticism in the press over the severity of the event, especially the conduct of Robert Carlin in remounting Dictator when witnesses described the horse as distressed.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] His cause of death was recorded as a burst blood vessel.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] For many years it was believed that the silks worn by Mason were blue with black cap.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] However, when the original silks were restored and presented to the Aintree museum, they were found to have actually been scarlet.
[src:2023-grand-national/1839-grand-national] It was found that John Elmore changed his colours to blue in the late 1840s, which led to the mistaken belief.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] Although recorded by the press at the time as the fifth running of the Grand Liverpool, which was renamed the Grand National in 1847, the first three runnings were poorly organised affairs.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] The race was not run as a handicap chase and therefore all the runners were declared to carry 12 stone.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] The course was laid out with eleven obstacles in total with the competitors starting from the bend at the end of the finishing straight beside the stables.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] The first obstacle was an iron rail of 3 feet 5 inches into the Melling Road.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] The runners then jumped out of the road over a hedge and ditch 7 feet 11 inches high.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] The third fence was also a ditch some ten feet wide and the fourth an even bigger ditch of 16 feet to clear.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] Fence five was a slightly smaller ditch before the runners cleared an obstacle of little consequence to be considered an actual fence.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] The fence that would gradually come to be known as Becher's Brook was next with a clearance of 20 feet.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] The runners then turned sharply towards the Canal over a considerable jump with a steep landing side.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] The eighth fence was the second brook and ran along the canal side, this was followed by a ditch and rail with a thirteen-foot span.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] The tenth fence was a leap into the Anchor Bridge and almost instantly straight back out again to bring the runners back towards the stands and the only fence on the course, a dry stone wall rising from 4 foot 6 inches to 4 foot 10 on the outside.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] The runners then set off to jump the first ten fences, along with other insignificant obstacles before bypassing the wall on the run to the finish post.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] The majority of the course was plough land with turf only on the racecourse proper and it was speculated by witnesses that the majority of the fences had been lowered slightly from last year in the wake of criticism.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] The competitors reached the newly named Becher's Brook without incident where **Cruickshank** stumbled on landing and was cannoned into by **Weathercock** with both falling.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] The former was remounted by his jockey, Guy, albeit with a severely bloodied nose while the latter's rider, Barker was carried unconscious to Seed's farmhouse nearby.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] Last year's champion **Lottery** reached the stone wall in front of the stands in second place but clipped the top of the obstacle, falling amid a flurry of dismantled masonry.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] All three horses following immediately behind were caught in the melee and were brought down, the three being **Columbine**, favourite **The Nun** and **Seventy-four**.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] Powell remounted the favourite but was forced to pull up before setting off on the second circuit when she was found to be lame while Olliver was taken to the stands with a broken collar bone and concussion.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] The pileup allowed **Valentine** to re-establish a lead of many lengths over the rest of the field but he was caught shortly before reaching Becher's for the second time by **Jerry** and **Arthur** with the remaining competitors too far behind to be able to issue a challenge.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] **Arthur** fell heavily at the brook, leaving **Jerry** to canter home over the remaining fences to win as he liked.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] **Arthur** was quickly remounted and although he caught **Valentine** before jumping the final hurdle he was unable to make up the ground on **Jerry** and finished second by four lengths with **Valentine** the same distance behind in third.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] The remaining runners had not reached the distance chair situated beside the wall fence by the time the third horse had passed the post, thus these runners were officially declared as non finishers.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] Those who did pass the post were, in order, **Cruickshank**, **Hasty**, **The Sea** and **Spolasco**.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] The last horse had fallen during the second circuit and was remounted while **The Augean** also fell at some point during the second circuit.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] Despite winning in a very comfortable manner, and slowing to a canter a long way before the finish, **Jerry** still finished in a time of twelve minutes and thirty seconds, shattering the course record by a minute and a half.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] Again the press were very critical of the race, especially noting the incident at the wall where many spectators had thought Tom Olliver had been killed by his fall, so bad was his state when being carried away to the stands.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] Furthermore, it was later discovered that Barker had been left unattended in a barn near Seed's farm where none of the connections of his mount had made any enquiry as to his state.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] As a result, the wall was replaced with a water jump in time for the next running.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] Later historical accounts of the Grand National are notorious for carrying factual errors.
[src:2023-grand-national/1840-grand-national] The official history of the race written in the 1980s recorded Cruickshank as a non runner and The Sea as an official finisher in fourth place.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] Although recorded by the press at the time as the sixth running of the Grand Liverpool, which was renamed the Grand National in 1847, the first three runnings were poorly organised affairs.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] The race was not run as a handicap chase and therefore all the runners were declared to carry 12 stone with the exception of the winner of the 1840 Cheltenham Steeplechase who had to carry 13 stone 4 lbs.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] The runners would set off from a grass field near Seeds lane and jump a small first fence before turning slightly right to jump a further four fences down a line of wheat fields to the first brook, described only as being familiar to Captain Beecher.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] The runners then proceeded left over a fallow field to take the seventh jump into a grass field to turn sharp left at the eighth obstacle, later to be known as the Canal Turn.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] Three further flights followed along the Canalside that took the runners over a large grass enclosure before jumping into and then out of the Melling Lane to re-enter the racecourse at its far extreme, known as the training ground.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] Once back in front of the stands, the runners took a hurdle at the site of the distance judge before leaping an artificial brook, which had replaced the wall, being the fifteenth obstacle.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] The competitors would then cover the same course again, with the exception of the artificial brook, which was bypassed on the run-in.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] The course was as it had been the previous year with the exception that the wall, situated in front of the stands, was replaced with an artificial water jump.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] Officially **Lottery** is recorded as favourite on officially good going.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] The race was started two hours late at 3 pm with **Selim** setting off at a pace considered good for a flat race.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] He earned a ten-length advantage by Becher's Brook and was still travelling well when he was considered unlucky to land on boggy ground when jumping out of the last fallow field into the grass at the Canalside, the eleventh jump on the course, causing him to fall and lose his lead.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] On turning back out into the country for the second time **Legacy** took up the running again.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] **Cigar**, **Peter Simple** and **Oliver Twist** adopted a different route down to Becher's Brook to the rest of the runners and bypassed the first jump, which was allowed, as long as the competitors raced outside the course marking flags.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] However, no real advantage, other than missing one fence, appears to have been made and the two groups were quickly reunited to jump the remaining fences to Becher's.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] By this stage **Selim** had made up the ground lost when falling and went back into the lead at the fence before the Brook.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] At the fence before the Canal Turn **Oliver Twist** fell and may have hampered **Cigar** who was the only runner continuing who was detached from the main body, but he was able to get back the lost lengths to move into second behind **Charity** when **Selim** began to fade along the Canalside.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] **Cigar**, **Charity** and **Lottery** jumped the fence out of the lane together before **Charity** kicked on to three-length lead on entering the racecourse.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] Most of the field had every chance at this stage but the injection of pace now told on most of the competitors, and with a quarter-mile to run **Charity** had only the two greys in the race **Peter Simple** and **Cigar** challenging him.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] Note: No official returns were given for any runner outside the first three.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] Four competitors claimed to have finished fourth in a tight finish, in which the decision was given to Revealer.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] No attempt was made to place the other three officially.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] The remaining runners, with the exception of Lottery, completed the course but had been stopped to a walk long before the finish and were swallowed up by the spectators, who entered the racecourse after the race.
[src:2023-grand-national/1841-grand-national] At the time, horses swallowed up by the crowd in such a manner were listed as distanced.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] The 1842 **Grand Liverpool Steeplechase** was the fourth official annual running of a steeplechase, later to become known as the Grand National Steeplechase, a horse race which took place at Aintree Racecourse near Liverpool on 2 March 1842 and attracted 15 runners.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] Although recorded by the press at the time as the seventh running of the Grand Liverpool, which was renamed the Grand National in 1847, the first three runnings were poorly organised affairs and are today regarded as unofficial.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] The remaining runners did not command a starting price from the bookmakers and were sent off unquoted.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] The course consisted of two circuits of a spindle-shaped course at Aintree, starting from a position beyond the modern Melling Road, then known as the Sunken Lane, and into open countryside.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] The competitors would have to negotiate any hedges and banks they came across to travel from field to field, most of which were open ploughland, until reaching Becher's Brook, a man-made post and rail.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] From here the field then turned left towards the Leeds to Liverpool canal, before jumping the Canal Turn, a fence at a sharp 90-degree angle.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] This would then place the runners in the fields running along the canal, where they would jump Valentine's Brook, The Tabletop, a fence in which the landing side was significantly raised, and then across the lane at Anchor Bridge to re-enter the racecourse.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] From here, the land was laid to turf as the runners turned left and came back towards the stands.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] Here they had to negotiate the monument or make a fence, today known as the chair, and then a water jump before setting off on a second circuit of the course.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] The start of the second circuit was marked by the Sunken Lane, a bank into and then out of what is now Melling Road.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] The rest of the second circuit was the same as the first until turning back onto the racecourse.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] On reaching the race course for a second time, the runners would this time jump two hurdles before a long run into the finish line, bypassing the monument fence and water jump on the way.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] At the start of the second circuit, **Honesty** refused at the bank out of the Sunken Lane, where **Satirist** also fell.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] **Peter Simple** took up the running, and by the time Becher's Brook was reached for the second time, the competitors were spread out over a furlong of the course.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] At the turn for home a group of spectators, keen to get a good view, had encroached onto the course without realising.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] **Peter Simple** was by now many lengths clear but his rider failed to notice the spectators in time and in trying to avoid them he was thrown from his mount.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] Powell, on second-placed **Seventy Four** was able to take evasive action and continued towards the hurdles in the lead with only **Gaylad** close enough to challenge.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] The race was timed at 13 minutes and 30 seconds, a full minute outside the record.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] Colours as published in *The Liverpool Mail*, Thursday 3 March 1842.
[src:2023-grand-national/1842-grand-national] Distanced refers to horses that was not in the sight of the judge when the first horse reached the chair.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] The **2023 Grand National** (officially known as the **Randox 2023 Grand National** for sponsorship reasons) was the 175th annual running of the Grand National horse race.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] It took place on Saturday 15 April 2023, at Aintree Racecourse near Liverpool, England.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] The event was sponsored by Randox Health with Natasha Jonas acting as ambassador.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] The race was won by Corach Rambler who was trained by Lucinda Russell in Scotland and ridden by Irish jockey Derek Fox, who had both previously won the Grand National in 2017 with One For Arthur.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] The race start was delayed by 14 minutes, following protests by campaign group Animal Rising, the first such disruptions since the cancellation of the 1993 Grand National due to a series of false starts and the 1997 Grand National due to the IRA bomb threat.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Merseyside Police made 118 arrests, for both "criminal damage and public nuisance offences".
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] The initial entry of 85 horses was published on 7 February 2023.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Only 31 of the horses entered were trained in Great Britain, compared to 54 in the initial entry for the 2022 race.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Of the Irish-trained runners, 21 were trained by Gordon Elliott, who was seeking a fourth Grand National victory as a trainer.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Bookmakers made 2022 winner Noble Yeats 10-1 favourite at the time of the entries.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Weight for the race were announced on 21 February 2023.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Three horses were given the top weight of 11 stones and 12 pounds; Any Second Now (the 2022 runner-up), Conflated and Hewick.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Galvin and Noble Yeats were just behind on 11 stone 11, and Noble Yeats remained the betting favourite at a best price of 11-1.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Publication of the weights opened up the possibility that the final field would be dominated by Irish-trained runners, with 41 of the top 60 in the weights trained in Ireland.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Nine horses were withdrawn at the acceptance stage on 7 March.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Amongst the withdrawals were the 2021 winner Minella Times, who had been retired, and the fourth-placed horse from 2021 Burrows Saint.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Iwilldoit was withdrawn having failed to meet the requirements of running in six steeplechases before 19 February.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] The withdrawals left 73 possible runners remaining with the next acceptance stage due on 28 March.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] A further sixteen horses were withdrawn at the 28 March acceptance stage to leave 57 possible runners.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] The fifth-placed horse from 2021, Farclas, was amongst the withdrawals and other notable scratchings included Becher Chase winner Ashtown Lad and the 2022 Irish Grand National winner Lord Lariat.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] The betting at this stage was headed by 6-1 chance Corach Rambler, who had won the Ultima Handicap Chase for a second consecutive year, followed by Noble Yeats at 8-1.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Only Any Second Now remained from the three top-weighted horses as Conflated and Hewick were withdrawn.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Final confirmations were made on 10 April and seven more horses were withdrawn, leaving 50 possible runners.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Corach Rambler remained as the general 6-1 betting favourite with Noble Yeats at 8-1 and Delta Work at 10-1.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] The 40 runners were finalised on Thursday 13 April.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] There were no withdrawals at Thursday's declaration stage.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] In a change from previous years, no reserves were declared.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Escaria Ten, who finished ninth in the 2022 race, was declared a non-runner on the day.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] lead commentator Richard Hoiles describes the climax of the race.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] As the Grand National is accorded the status of an event of national interest in the United Kingdom and is listed on the Ofcom Code on Sports and Other Listed and Designated Events, it must be shown on free-to-air terrestrial television in the UK.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] The race was broadcast live on TV by ITV for the sixth time, and the final year in its current three year deal with the British Horseracing Authority.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] The ITV coverage was presented by Ed Chamberlin and Adele Mulrennan.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Analysis was provided by former jockeys Sir Anthony McCoy, Mick Fitzgerald, Tom Scudamore, Harry Cobden and Ruby Walsh.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Reports were provided by Alice Plunkett, Luke Harvey, Rishi Persad and Matt Chapman, and betting updates were provided by Brian Gleeson.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Oli Bell and Chris Hughes covered viewers' comments on social media, while Mark Heyes and Charlotte Hawkins were chatting to the crowd on Ladies Day.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] The commentary team was Mark Johnson, Stewart Machin and Richard Hoiles, who called the finish for the sixth time.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Following the race, Bell and Walsh guided viewers on a fence-by-fence re-run of the race.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Hill Sixteen fell and was mortally injured at the first fence, killing him almost instantly.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] The trainer of Hill Sixteen, Sandy Thomson, claimed that the horse became "hyper" because of the protests, which led to him not taking off at the first fence.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Thomson was adamant that the actions of the protesters were behind his horse falling for the first time in his career.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Hill Sixteen had previously ridden 27 races on 15 different tracks, and had previously jumped the Grand National fences at Aintree while competing twice in the Becher Chase .
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Earlier at the Aintree meeting Envoye Special had been euthanised, following an injury after a fall in the Foxhunters' Open Hunters' Chase and Dark Raven had been euthanised after a fall at the Turners Mersey Novice Hurdle.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Animal rights campaign group Animal Rising had threatened to disrupt the race and were protesting from early on the day of the race.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] 118 people were arrested over protests that delayed the start of race by 14 minutes.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] Merseyside Police held nine people who had been able to enter the track and later said arrests had been made for both "criminal damage and public nuisance offences", including arrests made before the race and connected to a protest that had blocked the M57.
[src:2023-grand-national/2023-grand-national] This was the third Grand National to be disrupted in post-war history since the 1993 Grand National which led to a series of false starts and the 1997 Grand National was postponed to Monday because of an IRA bomb threat.
